56
00:04:01,596 --> 00:04:06,921
And so, I will get back to this map a little bit later, but I know for myself, as a total geek,

57
00:04:07,262 --> 00:04:13,367
and also someone who's very interested in maps, it was Tolkien's map that actually led me to pursue cartography as a career,

58
00:04:13,427 --> 00:04:21,395
because I just love the fact that he made something completely unreal look completely real by using a method of cartography.

59
00:04:22,822 --> 00:04:28,226
And of course there's a lot of other storytellers that have come along that have done their own versions.

60
00:04:28,266 --> 00:04:30,508
A lot of fantasy worlds.

61
00:04:30,869 --> 00:04:34,672
How many fantasy worlds when you open up the first book of the series there's a map?

62
00:04:35,212 --> 00:04:41,298
Because it's like the writer is trying to show you that this is a realized version of my imagination.

63
00:04:41,318 --> 00:04:44,901
I love this Google Maps version of Westeros. It's really cool.

64
00:04:46,300 --> 00:04:50,263
You know, whatever it might be, there's all of these fictional realms that people have

65
00:04:50,303 --> 00:04:53,785
created a lot in literature, in film, or wherever you want them to be.

66
00:04:53,805 --> 00:05:00,369
And I could go on for days and days with examples, but basically in a lot of these cases, the

67
00:05:00,429 --> 00:05:04,432
realism that they're trying to create in the world that they're trying to build for you

68
00:05:04,532 --> 00:05:08,875
to present their narrative, to present their story, is to give a sense of authenticity.

69
00:05:09,275 --> 00:05:12,717
It's almost like when they're showing you the map in their book or whatever it might

70
00:05:12,757 --> 00:05:15,159
be, it's almost as if they're saying, I was there.

71
00:05:15,939 --> 00:05:21,081
I saw these things. I made this map. It's almost that's why one of the brilliance of

72
00:05:21,201 --> 00:05:26,143
Tolkien's vision is that Tolkien's map. It's almost like it feels so real that he was there

73
00:05:26,243 --> 00:05:32,365
He actually did the cartography because he went there and so to be able to convey that sense because as cartographers

74
00:05:32,405 --> 00:05:36,707
That's exactly what we do. We have serving we have instruments that collect data

75
00:05:36,747 --> 00:05:40,268
We have satellites to do imagery of all these different methods now that collect

76
00:05:40,588 --> 00:05:43,553
the data and the cartographer compiles them into a map

77
00:05:43,853 --> 00:05:46,618
that basically is a way to say, hey look, we know what's there

78
00:05:47,199 --> 00:05:50,003
or the cartographer themselves would say I was there

79
00:05:50,384 --> 00:05:53,428
although in these days it's not really the case anymore because so many things

80
00:05:53,469 --> 00:05:54,831
are automated with cartography

81
00:05:55,857 --> 00:05:59,158
And of course, being a geek of, you know, this is in Norway,

82
00:05:59,478 --> 00:06:03,140
we also ascribe fictional place to real place as well,

83
00:06:03,200 --> 00:06:05,541
because they become so ingrained in popular culture,

84
00:06:05,581 --> 00:06:07,622
and the world that was realized on the screen

85
00:06:08,022 --> 00:06:11,723
is also a world that has been somewhat realized on the ground.

86
00:06:12,504 --> 00:06:15,365
Or like going to Tunisia and being there on Tatooine,

87
00:06:15,745 --> 00:06:18,506
which I know Tunisian friends, they know it's Tunisia,

88
00:06:18,546 --> 00:06:20,927
it's not Tatooine, stop calling us Tatooine.

89
00:06:21,327 --> 00:06:26,589
But it's just such a real place because of what was constructed and the narrative that was built around it.

90
00:06:27,770 --> 00:06:31,751
One of the things I really want to emphasize about worldbuilding, it is not about realism.

91
00:06:32,511 --> 00:06:35,172
It's really about realization over realism.

92
00:06:35,192 --> 00:06:42,095
Because I think a lot of times, when I've talked and worked with a lot of developers on many, many franchises over the past 20 years,

93
00:06:42,615 --> 00:06:45,836
a lot of them tend to focus on the realism aspect, that worldbuilding...

94
00:06:46,656 --> 00:06:49,197
equals detail. That's not the case at all.

95
00:06:49,497 --> 00:06:53,158
Detail is a function of what serves the narrative later on, and we'll talk about

96
00:06:53,218 --> 00:06:53,958
detail later,

97
00:06:54,378 --> 00:06:57,999
but it's really about the notion of realization. What does the world need to

98
00:06:58,059 --> 00:06:58,860
be to serve

99
00:06:59,220 --> 00:07:02,120
the narrative that you want to create and what the experience

100
00:07:02,441 --> 00:07:03,221
you want to convey?

101
00:07:04,122 --> 00:07:10,525
And so really it's a function of taking the narrative goals that you have, because generally speaking there is a narrative.

102
00:07:10,625 --> 00:07:14,267
Even in a game, something like Angry Birds, there is a narrative in that game.

103
00:07:14,727 --> 00:07:20,470
And, you know, maybe at first it really wasn't there, but you can kind of get some sense of it.

104
00:07:20,570 --> 00:07:23,231
Even in like, you play something like Bejeweled Blitz.

105
00:07:23,791 --> 00:07:26,733
It's not necessarily meant to be a narrative-driven game,

106
00:07:26,753 --> 00:07:30,336
but there is a kind of underlying lore in that game,

107
00:07:30,396 --> 00:07:33,098
like the different levels and the names of the levels and things like that.

108
00:07:33,118 --> 00:07:36,060
And it kind of makes you wonder, what does this relate to?

109
00:07:36,100 --> 00:07:37,741
It doesn't really matter because I'm going to go play again.

110
00:07:38,242 --> 00:07:38,762
But, um...

111
00:07:39,512 --> 00:07:44,697
So you take the narrative goals and you also take the goals of the experience, because these are distinct things.

112
00:07:45,378 --> 00:07:48,560
So, for example, I'm not going to go into this topic because there's no time for it,

113
00:07:48,921 --> 00:07:55,526
but a lot of VR right now, a lot of VR demonstrations that we've seen, to me, are experiences, they're not narratives.

114
00:07:55,827 --> 00:08:00,611
There are things where you have a certain feeling, a certain experience within that space,

115
00:08:00,631 --> 00:08:06,576
but it's not really conveying a narrative, a plot, or some kind of, you know, we're getting there, we are getting there slowly.

116
00:08:07,197 --> 00:08:12,959
But in a lot of games that we make, though, it is a combination of this notion of we have a narrative for the space,

117
00:08:13,039 --> 00:08:16,861
and we have a space in which we want certain things to be experienced by the player.

118
00:08:17,521 --> 00:08:22,244
Those things may not always relate to the core narrative. Sometimes they will, and sometimes they won't.

119
00:08:22,804 --> 00:08:25,765
But ultimately, it kind of helps shape what does the world need to be,

120
00:08:26,145 --> 00:08:29,967
what does it have to be realized in order for this world to work for your vision.

121
00:08:31,140 --> 00:08:33,521
So there's a quick recipe for realizing worlds.

122
00:08:33,581 --> 00:08:36,002
So we're going to talk in some detail about some of these.

123
00:08:36,502 --> 00:08:39,103
So, and this is, I'm presenting this like a recipe.

124
00:08:39,163 --> 00:08:41,624
So first you start with a suggestion of familiarity.

125
00:08:42,024 --> 00:08:44,765
So, you know, going back to Tolkien's map as an example,

126
00:08:44,825 --> 00:08:46,885
his map looks like it could be something real.

127
00:08:46,945 --> 00:08:49,646
It's not completely fantastical like Dr. Seuss.

128
00:08:50,146 --> 00:08:53,387
I mean, it looks like something that could be familiar to us

129
00:08:53,547 --> 00:08:56,588
because we're used to seeing maps that are drawn like that,

130
00:08:56,608 --> 00:08:58,389
or we're used to seeing mountain ranges like that.

131
00:08:59,149 --> 00:09:05,951
We also take a hint of complex systems. So a lot of worlds, we know that our world is incredibly complex.

132
00:09:05,971 --> 00:09:09,652
There are so many interrelated systems and complexity out there.

133
00:09:09,672 --> 00:09:13,994
We cannot represent all of those in a game, but we kind of hint at those by different things.

134
00:09:14,034 --> 00:09:17,195
There's all kinds of techniques that we do that, by artifacts that are in the environment,

135
00:09:17,515 --> 00:09:21,076
by hints that are dropped in the narrative, by characters that show up,

136
00:09:21,116 --> 00:09:25,897
and maybe the characters reveal a certain aspect of that world that the player had no idea existed.

137
00:09:27,010 --> 00:09:28,831
We also have a dash of cultural evidence.

138
00:09:28,911 --> 00:09:32,412
So oftentimes, because a lot of games do involve some kind of culture,

139
00:09:32,452 --> 00:09:37,014
whether it actually involves people, whether it involves aliens or animals or whatever it might be,

140
00:09:37,054 --> 00:09:40,815
there's a sense of culture that there's been an inhabitants,

141
00:09:40,855 --> 00:09:43,476
there has been some kind of presence in this game.

142
00:09:43,757 --> 00:09:46,978
It's not just an open biosphere of animals and plants.

143
00:09:47,058 --> 00:09:50,379
There's something else there that kind of makes it evidence.

144
00:09:50,419 --> 00:09:54,841
I mean, I think like the Halo games were, in my opinion, were very cool in this way

145
00:09:54,901 --> 00:09:55,401
because they were...

146
00:09:55,801 --> 00:09:58,646
the Forerunner artifacts that were strewn around the Halo ring

147
00:09:58,926 --> 00:10:01,270
that kind of gave evidence that something had happened here

148
00:10:01,451 --> 00:10:05,637
but we never really got to know, at least in the initial games, what was going on.

149
00:10:06,900 --> 00:10:10,062
And we need a big chunk of logical consistency in the recipe.

150
00:10:10,162 --> 00:10:14,406
And I will talk more specifically about, I'm going to talk more specifically about cultural

151
00:10:14,526 --> 00:10:18,830
evidence, logical consistency, and the other one, which is a pinch of topology.

152
00:10:19,210 --> 00:10:23,794
Topology means connectedness, and if you've heard the term topology, oftentimes we hear

153
00:10:24,014 --> 00:10:30,039
in network topology, where network engineers talk about the connectedness of devices.

154
00:10:30,439 --> 00:10:35,583
In geography, we use topology as a sense of connectedness of things, of attributes, of

155
00:10:35,683 --> 00:10:36,144
places.

156
00:10:36,784 --> 00:10:38,945
And again, I'll talk about that more.

157
00:10:39,865 --> 00:10:40,825
Now cultural evidence.

158
00:10:40,865 --> 00:10:44,907
So basically what this means is taking the minimum amount of content you need to convey

159
00:10:44,947 --> 00:10:46,467
the presence of an in-game culture.

160
00:10:46,987 --> 00:10:49,688
So this is really key to setting the context of the game.

161
00:10:50,228 --> 00:10:53,229
So and I'll give an example in a minute.

162
00:10:54,669 --> 00:11:00,453
This requires logical consistency to be effective, and so you're going to need to know what that is.

163
00:11:00,513 --> 00:11:01,633
We'll talk about that in a minute.

164
00:11:02,594 --> 00:11:06,997
The highest risk to activity in game development today, in my opinion, doing this kind of work,

165
00:11:07,458 --> 00:11:10,159
is this notion of building cultural evidence in a game.

166
00:11:10,560 --> 00:11:12,041
So let me explain a little bit more.

167
00:11:13,029 --> 00:11:16,413
Let's say for example, the writers, the narrative designers wrote the script.

168
00:11:16,973 --> 00:11:20,718
So you've got the script, you know what the characters are going to do, you know what they're going to say.

169
00:11:20,758 --> 00:11:27,225
You know the basic plot, maybe you know what vehicles are going to be needed, or weapons, or whatever it might be, artifacts, all that kind of stuff.

170
00:11:27,766 --> 00:11:30,949
But then, you kind of let loose the designers and artists and say,

171
00:11:30,969 --> 00:11:32,491
okay, make this world feel real.

172
00:11:33,052 --> 00:11:38,636
Real make it feel realized make it feel like it actually exists in something, you know

173
00:11:38,656 --> 00:11:44,981
That's not just you know, some line John's on paper lines John on paper without much detail in there

174
00:11:45,021 --> 00:11:47,803
So we kind of backfill this notion of backfilling

175
00:11:47,843 --> 00:11:52,367
So for example, like if you have like a middle medieval environment, you don't just have the buildings

176
00:11:52,747 --> 00:11:57,151
You might have like stacks of hay. You might have some barrels. You might have some other stuff

177
00:11:57,171 --> 00:12:02,255
You might have some banners hanging from buildings and flags. You might have little animals running around

178
00:12:02,735 --> 00:12:07,718
All of this kind of detail that fills in the world and kind of gives it a sense of actuality,

179
00:12:08,559 --> 00:12:09,980
that's what I call backfilling.

180
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:15,864
And this is a very high-risk activity because oftentimes it's not checked by the main designers of the game.

181
00:12:15,904 --> 00:12:17,345
And so a lot of times...

182
00:12:18,186 --> 00:12:21,168
Game developers are under so much time pressure to do this activity

183
00:12:21,188 --> 00:12:23,871
that they just start throwing stuff in there as much as they can.

184
00:12:23,911 --> 00:12:25,452
Of course, this depends on the game.

185
00:12:25,472 --> 00:12:27,074
If the game is going to be hyper-detailed,

186
00:12:27,354 --> 00:12:30,657
they're going to be under incredible pressure to fill in the game.

187
00:12:30,717 --> 00:12:34,841
Think of a game like Skyrim and the amount of stuff that is in Skyrim.

188
00:12:34,961 --> 00:12:39,605
Pots and papers and books with text in them and all that kind of stuff.

189
00:12:40,086 --> 00:12:44,092
All of that has to be realized in the process of building the cultural evidence for that world,

190
00:12:44,472 --> 00:12:48,218
because that's what helps Skyrim feel like an actual realized place.

191
00:12:49,940 --> 00:12:54,427
And so this can be a risky activity because people just kind of randomly create things.

192
00:12:55,608 --> 00:12:59,130
There's two key tips for creating evidence that I'll pass along right away.

193
00:12:59,410 --> 00:13:00,911
One is you don't be lazy.

194
00:13:00,931 --> 00:13:03,272
And I'm sorry, but that's the only word for it.

195
00:13:03,372 --> 00:13:06,314
So, and I'll give you an example in just a minute about being lazy.

196
00:13:06,354 --> 00:13:08,556
So you need to create everything with a purpose.

197
00:13:08,616 --> 00:13:10,857
It's not just, we'll just throw some barrels in there.

198
00:13:10,877 --> 00:13:11,878
It's like, why?

199
00:13:11,898 --> 00:13:13,559
Why are the barrels there?

200
00:13:13,579 --> 00:13:14,900
Which leads to the second point.

201
00:13:15,100 --> 00:13:16,100
Ask questions.

202
00:13:16,501 --> 00:13:17,601
So it's really important.

203
00:13:17,901 --> 00:13:22,044
And I know it's very difficult in the game industry to ask an artist, for example,

204
00:13:22,064 --> 00:13:23,825
it's like, why did you draw the character that way?

205
00:13:24,105 --> 00:13:25,026
I don't understand that.

206
00:13:25,406 --> 00:13:31,009
Because we have a mutual respect for creative vision, but at the same time there are certain

207
00:13:31,089 --> 00:13:35,471
points at which it's completely valid to ask, why does it look that way?

208
00:13:35,832 --> 00:13:37,072
What does that symbol mean?

209
00:13:37,673 --> 00:13:38,853
What does that flag mean?

210
00:13:38,913 --> 00:13:40,494
Why is that faction green?

211
00:13:40,514 --> 00:13:44,636
I mean, questions like that, just because you have an understanding to basically...

212
00:13:45,317 --> 00:13:49,338
Understand your own complexity and not just make it a random act.

213
00:13:49,838 --> 00:13:54,220
And I'll kind of get into a little bit later why random acts of creation can be dangerous.

214
00:13:55,320 --> 00:13:57,361
So here's a cultural evidence piece.

215
00:13:57,421 --> 00:14:01,242
So this is a screenshot from Jade Empire.

216
00:14:01,262 --> 00:14:06,324
And Jade Empire was a pan-Asian world that supposedly had nothing to do with our world

217
