other than kind of felt like it was Asian.

218
00:14:09,125 --> 00:14:12,566
And I won't go into all the complexity of making this game, but it was a real challenge.

219
00:14:12,967 --> 00:14:15,648
You can see these glowing blue cylinders on the side there.

220
00:14:15,888 --> 00:14:18,589
Well, this was an aspect of the backfilling of the game.

221
00:14:18,649 --> 00:14:22,530
So what they did is because it was a pan-Asian environment,

222
00:14:22,570 --> 00:14:28,152
they threw prayer wheels from Tibetan Buddhism into this hallway.

223
00:14:29,753 --> 00:14:33,536
There wasn't Buddhism in this game, okay? This is not the real world.

224
00:14:33,616 --> 00:14:39,161
So they threw these artifacts into the environment just to make kind of flesh it out and add something there.

225
00:14:39,641 --> 00:14:43,284
And yet that was not part of this world. It's not valid.

226
00:14:43,764 --> 00:14:47,067
And so, you know, this is what the actual prayer wheels look like.

227
00:14:47,267 --> 00:14:50,610
And so the previous ones, they actually did look like prayer wheels,

228
00:14:50,670 --> 00:14:53,532
but then they kind of fixed it and made this blue weird glow.

229
00:14:53,572 --> 00:14:54,893
So it looks like this energy.

230
00:14:55,434 --> 00:14:58,936
thing going on. But this is an example of an artist kind of throwing something

231
00:14:58,996 --> 00:14:59,597
there and saying, well,

232
00:14:59,877 --> 00:15:03,079
this whole environment looks kinda like Tibetan Buddhism, so I'm gonna put prayer

233
00:15:03,099 --> 00:15:03,660
wheels in there.

234
00:15:03,940 --> 00:15:06,802
But those prayer wheels have a specific meaning in the real world

235
00:15:07,142 --> 00:15:09,945
and they probably don't belong in a game that has a more fantasy setting.

236
00:15:11,840 --> 00:15:18,825
Logical consistency. This is incredibly important. If there is one thing that I see game designers and artists and writers do wrong,

237
00:15:19,166 --> 00:15:23,569
more than anything else when they're creating a world, is they don't build in logical consistency.

238
00:15:23,949 --> 00:15:30,254
So this is basically the notion that rules exist and are applied to the space, time, and all elements within that world.

239
00:15:30,554 --> 00:15:35,798
This is something Tolkien did really well, even though, yeah, there's some exceptions there, and I'm going to point one out in a little bit.

240
00:15:36,419 --> 00:15:41,060
But there is a sense that the world works, that there is a system that works.

241
00:15:41,100 --> 00:15:45,222
Just like the way our world, we know certain things work in certain ways.

242
00:15:45,262 --> 00:15:47,843
We know how plate tectonics works, more or less.

243
00:15:48,223 --> 00:15:50,144
We know kind of how the weather sort of works.

244
00:15:50,184 --> 00:15:54,005
We know how transportation systems seem to go right or wrong.

245
00:15:54,465 --> 00:15:55,786
We know all that kind of stuff.

246
00:15:55,846 --> 00:16:00,628
And so that helps a world feel real by building in ecological consistency.

247
00:16:02,262 --> 00:16:09,024
There's a lack of contradiction in the system, so it's like you're not going to come across something that just makes no sense at all in the world.

248
00:16:09,064 --> 00:16:13,385
It's like the things that are in the world feel like they're supposed to be in that world.

249
00:16:14,305 --> 00:16:17,826
There's also a lack of conflict between the content elements that comprise the world.

250
00:16:17,906 --> 00:16:24,407
So, you know, if you're not going to have something where it feels completely incongruous,

251
00:16:24,427 --> 00:16:25,448
that you'd have a culture...

252
00:16:27,127 --> 00:16:36,176
You know, you'd have like a culture that represents, that is like from the Nordic areas, from a cold area, living in a complete hot desert area.

253
00:16:36,917 --> 00:16:40,300
Something like that. I mean, maybe there's a reason for it, but that's what I'm saying. Where's the logic?

254
00:16:40,440 --> 00:16:45,424
So if you're going to do something like that, make sure there's a logic for doing it, because that kind of stuff...

255
00:16:45,945 --> 00:16:48,407
you know, does tend to kick the player out of the experience.

256
00:16:48,447 --> 00:16:49,627
And they kind of step back and say,

257
00:16:49,647 --> 00:16:51,349
WTF, I don't understand this.

258
00:16:51,389 --> 00:16:52,710
This doesn't make any sense to me.

259
00:16:52,990 --> 00:16:54,671
It doesn't really have a sense of realness,

260
00:16:55,071 --> 00:16:57,173
which in that sense of realness and the realization

261
00:16:57,233 --> 00:16:58,734
helps draw players into the game.

262
00:16:58,754 --> 00:17:02,517
And we also want to talk about the fidelity relationships

263
00:17:02,577 --> 00:17:04,838
between, whoa, slow down there, Tex.

264
00:17:06,039 --> 00:17:07,360
Sorry, I don't know what just happened there.

265
00:17:09,622 --> 00:17:11,963
So, yeah, that's unfortunate.

266
00:17:13,169 --> 00:17:16,550
So anyway, so we also want to talk about topology.

267
00:17:17,371 --> 00:17:19,392
But here's an example of logical consistency.

268
00:17:19,992 --> 00:17:23,434
So, this is kind of like the example from Jade Empire.

269
00:17:23,494 --> 00:17:26,816
So this is from Cameo, which was on the original Xbox.

270
00:17:26,876 --> 00:17:29,758
You can see here, and now this is another world

271
00:17:29,798 --> 00:17:31,919
that had absolutely nothing to do with our world.

272
00:17:31,979 --> 00:17:33,440
It's a complete fantasy world.

273
00:17:33,920 --> 00:17:39,385
And so, is it logical that you would have grave markers that are wooden crosses in this world?

274
00:17:39,985 --> 00:17:44,468
Maybe. Maybe there's a good reason why there's wooden crosses being used in this particular universe.

275
00:17:44,508 --> 00:17:49,152
But I can tell you the answer was, is that this was a case of creative laziness.

276
00:17:49,212 --> 00:17:52,134
The artist, when I pointed this out, saying, what are those supposed to be?

277
00:17:52,154 --> 00:17:54,316
And they said, well, of course, they're grave markers.

278
00:17:54,336 --> 00:17:58,359
I said, what do you mean, of course? There's no Christianity in this universe, so how would I know that?

279
00:17:58,879 --> 00:18:01,801
And their answer to me was, what else would I use?

280
00:18:01,821 --> 00:18:02,622
And I'm like...

281
00:18:03,544 --> 00:18:07,030
I don't know, you're the artist, maybe you draw something different.

282
00:18:08,813 --> 00:18:12,699
So that's one of those things where this is not logically consistent with the universe.

283
00:18:12,739 --> 00:18:16,005
It has no place there, it's a content element that really should not be there.

284
00:18:17,294 --> 00:18:22,817
And of course topology, so this is essential, this is kind of a more subtle point to world

285
00:18:22,857 --> 00:18:26,740
building where there's a sense that things relate to one another.

286
00:18:26,840 --> 00:18:30,802
It's not like you just have all these random content elements, random cultures, random

287
00:18:30,943 --> 00:18:33,885
objects in the world that don't really seem to fit together.

288
00:18:33,905 --> 00:18:34,425
And so...

289
00:18:36,186 --> 00:18:41,047
I know I've heard some people accuse Tolkien, and I'm going to keep using Tolkien as an example,

290
00:18:41,067 --> 00:18:42,067
because he is a good example.

291
00:18:42,527 --> 00:18:46,648
I've heard some people accuse Tolkien of having a topology that sometimes feels weird.

292
00:18:46,668 --> 00:18:51,689
Because, like, why are there dwarves and elves and humans and all these things living in this?

293
00:18:51,829 --> 00:18:53,610
It doesn't seem to make sense.

294
00:18:53,650 --> 00:18:56,890
But if you read the Silmarillion, he kind of explains all of that.

295
00:18:56,950 --> 00:19:00,011
So he does have a whole backstory that explains why it's all there.

296
00:19:00,591 --> 00:19:04,512
So part of it is that the people who say that, it's like, well, you didn't get the full story.

297
00:19:04,532 --> 00:19:05,492
You need to go back and read.

298
00:19:06,553 --> 00:19:10,955
But topology is important because it gives us a sense of that interconnectedness of different things,

299
00:19:11,015 --> 00:19:13,396
like a culture, like the people to the land.

300
00:19:13,476 --> 00:19:18,279
How do the people in the game, if there is a people culture, how do they relate to the environment?

301
00:19:18,699 --> 00:19:22,021
Or are they just there without any kind of seeming connection?

302
00:19:22,381 --> 00:19:27,343
And we know that helps build a sense of realness to the game.

303
00:19:28,504 --> 00:19:31,966
And it applies to everything. It's not just about the relationship of places either.

304
00:19:32,006 --> 00:19:35,148
I'm not just talking about the actual distance between a place.

305
00:19:35,168 --> 00:19:39,171
That really doesn't matter because topology is agnostic of distance.

306
00:19:39,231 --> 00:19:41,072
It's all about the actual connection.

307
00:19:41,212 --> 00:19:43,854
What is connected to what and how is it connected to it?

308
00:19:45,604 --> 00:19:48,445
And so that's really important to kind of flesh that out.

309
00:19:49,285 --> 00:19:51,946
And it does help to convey a sense of a much broader universe.

310
00:19:52,006 --> 00:19:58,269
So even if you hint that there is a connection by dropping a line from a non-player character

311
00:19:58,289 --> 00:20:02,551
or by finding an artifact that seems to be, that might relate to different things in the

312
00:20:02,591 --> 00:20:07,134
game that kind of helps build the sense of lore, helps build a sense that this universe

313
00:20:07,194 --> 00:20:10,795
is a lot bigger than the player might initially imagine.

314
00:20:12,091 --> 00:20:14,713
So there's three core steps to world building that I want to cover.

315
00:20:14,733 --> 00:20:17,194
One is to set the context.

316
00:20:17,214 --> 00:20:21,237
So I'm actually going to spend a good deal of time on this issue of real world versus fictional world,

317
00:20:21,617 --> 00:20:25,260
because this tends to be one of the areas where I see a lot of designers get hung up,

318
00:20:25,740 --> 00:20:29,623
in terms of what they do next, in terms of how they build out their content.

319
00:20:30,483 --> 00:20:32,685
The second one is determine the level of complexity.

320
00:20:32,845 --> 00:20:37,169
So again, this is not about realism, it's about realization.

321
00:20:37,249 --> 00:20:41,773
How much is needed to actually make the world serve the narrative and serve the experience

322
00:20:41,813 --> 00:20:42,113
goals.

323
00:20:42,613 --> 00:20:44,595
And then lastly is about creating with intent.

324
00:20:44,655 --> 00:20:48,078
So then we talk about what you actually do, building the world layers.

325
00:20:48,458 --> 00:20:52,021
I'm not going to spend as much time on that part because that can go on for weeks.

326
00:20:52,442 --> 00:20:53,322
We don't have time for that.

327
00:20:53,803 --> 00:20:53,983
So

328
00:20:54,864 --> 00:20:58,106
Let's talk about this notion about real world and fictional world.

329
00:20:58,406 --> 00:21:02,829
Now, I realize this is a very strong dichotomy I'm putting here,

330
00:21:02,889 --> 00:21:05,931
but I do fully realize that this is a broad zone of overlap.

331
00:21:06,311 --> 00:21:10,414
It's very much the same way people are arguing about VR versus AR and blah blah blah.

332
00:21:10,774 --> 00:21:13,176
It's like it's a spectrum. There's certain degrees.

333
00:21:13,796 --> 00:21:18,620
overlap. I mean you could have things that take place in the real world like a lot of games do but there's a very

334
00:21:18,680 --> 00:21:24,044
fantastical, fantastical fictional things that happen on top of that real world.

335
00:21:24,384 --> 00:21:31,590
But my reason for making this dichotomy though is really important because if you base things in the real world in our world

336
00:21:31,610 --> 00:21:34,492
I keep saying real world. I don't want to get into some kind of

337
00:21:35,133 --> 00:21:37,074
metaphysical argument about that term today, but

338
00:21:38,922 --> 00:21:45,645
When you base things in our known world, it does have an effect on the content and the perception of the content

339
00:21:45,725 --> 00:21:47,765
and a lot of other things that we'll talk about.

340
00:21:47,785 --> 00:21:52,707
The fictional world, you have a lot more freedom, but it could also be dangerous because you also don't have boundaries.

341
00:21:53,207 --> 00:22:00,510
So you can basically kind of go off on a tangent and create something that might be completely problematic for people who are playing the game in our world.

342
00:22:01,770 --> 00:22:03,371
That was confusing really fast.

343
00:22:04,411 --> 00:22:04,711
Anyway...

344
00:22:05,537 --> 00:22:10,062
In the world of cartography, we know this very well, this whole fictional versus real world setting.

345
00:22:10,182 --> 00:22:13,806
So, you know, these are two versions of Google Maps.

346
00:22:13,946 --> 00:22:15,748
And Google was one of my clients.

347
00:22:15,788 --> 00:22:19,412
And when I was there, we were perfecting what we call domain tailoring.

348
00:22:19,452 --> 00:22:22,976
So you can see here in the US locale, when you go to Google Maps,

349
00:22:23,036 --> 00:22:27,501
and for most of the world, you see the northern area of India, Jammu and Kashmir, is disputed.

350
00:22:27,981 --> 00:22:31,202
You can see the dashed lines around the disputed territories up there,

351
00:22:31,222 --> 00:22:34,043
because it's disputed between Pakistan, India and China.

352
00:22:34,484 --> 00:22:39,486
Well, in India, by law, you must show Jammu and Kashmir as Indian territory.

353
00:22:39,546 --> 00:22:40,706
This is non-negotiable.

354
00:22:41,006 --> 00:22:44,088
You must do this or else your product will not sell in India.

355
00:22:44,128 --> 00:22:45,128
The government will ban it.

356
00:22:45,568 --> 00:22:49,210
And so, what I call this, this is what I call a geopolitical imagination.

357
00:22:49,490 --> 00:22:50,570
This doesn't exist.

358
00:22:50,930 --> 00:22:53,951
It exists in the political world of the Indian government,

359
00:22:53,971 --> 00:22:55,412
but it does not exist on the ground.

360
00:22:55,992 --> 00:22:58,835
And so this is in a way, this is kind of a fictional world.

361
00:22:59,275 --> 00:23:00,356
This doesn't really exist.

362
00:23:00,396 --> 00:23:02,958
So it might be almost as fictional as Tolkien's map.

363
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:09,123
So there's some differences between real world and fictional world and creation that I'm going to touch on.

364
00:23:09,443 --> 00:23:13,086
And again, for the sake of time, this is highly generalized.

365
00:23:13,487 --> 00:23:16,189
So that's another thing cartographers do, is we generalize a lot.

366
00:23:16,209 --> 00:23:19,492
Because you can't show everything on a map, so I'm generalizing my own talk a little bit.

367
00:23:20,052 --> 00:23:20,473
So anyway...

368
00:23:21,113 --> 00:23:25,296
Differences in world creation between doing real world and fictional world creation.

369
00:23:25,356 --> 00:23:30,360
So with the real world, the primary emphasis is often on replication and authenticity.

370
00:23:30,420 --> 00:23:32,502
So you want it to feel like it's a real place.

371
00:23:32,902 --> 00:23:35,744
There was a game like Six Days in Fallujah, which you may have heard about,

372
00:23:35,764 --> 00:23:41,149
which never got released because it perfectly recreated the battle of Fallujah in 2004 in Iraq.

373
00:23:41,549 --> 00:23:44,631
And it was controversial because of it, because it was a controversial battle.

374
00:23:45,092 --> 00:23:48,574
And the publisher was just like, I'm not touching this, we're not going to release this.

375
00:23:49,095 --> 00:23:53,316
And so it was very authentic and it replicated the city exactly

376
00:23:53,336 --> 00:23:56,736
and yet, you know, that was a problem for it.

377
00:23:57,197 --> 00:24:01,638
In the fictional world, the primary emphasis tends to be more on the imagination and distinctions.

378
00:24:01,678 --> 00:24:02,758
We want new things.

379
00:24:03,118 --> 00:24:05,658
We don't necessarily want stuff that we've already seen in the real world.

380
00:24:05,698 --> 00:24:07,639
We want to see things that have never existed before.

381
00:24:08,019 --> 00:24:09,959
That's where we kind of crank on our imagination.

382
00:24:10,319 --> 00:24:12,940
We want these things to be distinct from what we know in the real world

383
00:24:12,980 --> 00:24:16,541
because that distinction actually makes them, you know, stand out more.

384
00:24:17,602 --> 00:24:22,425
And in the consumption, basically on the player side, so the differences in the world consumption,

385
00:24:22,965 --> 00:24:29,489
is when you're playing a real-world game, it's basically the focus is on realism and

386
00:24:29,509 --> 00:24:33,691
the experience that feels genuine, like, wow, I'm really driving this tank, I'm really sniping

387
00:24:33,731 --> 00:24:36,172
that person's head off, you know, that kind of thing.

388
00:24:36,332 --> 00:24:37,573
I should use nicer examples.

389
00:24:41,235 --> 00:24:42,836
And what's wrong with me?

390
00:24:44,784 --> 00:24:49,207
And in the fictional world, it's often on, it's focused on discovery and escapism.

391
00:24:49,267 --> 00:24:52,669
So like, of course we all know that No Man's Sky just was released,

392
00:24:53,070 --> 00:24:57,733
and a lot of the both praise and criticism of the game is focused on that issue,

393
00:24:57,773 --> 00:25:01,015
that it's like too much discovery and too much escapism,

394
00:25:01,055 --> 00:25:03,417
but some people love that and some people don't.

395
00:25:03,637 --> 00:25:05,979
So then that's, you know, a whole different issue.

396
00:25:06,059 --> 00:25:09,962
But that tends to be what a lot of fictional worlds are more focused on,

397
00:25:10,502 --> 00:25:12,624
because that's one of the values of it.

398
00:25:14,045 --> 00:25:17,026
Discoverability, let me just touch on that issue really quick.

399
00:25:17,066 --> 00:25:21,869
So what I mean by discoverability, which is another critical issue when we're creating content,

400
00:25:21,929 --> 00:25:28,712
is when you have a content element in the game, let's say it's something that could be potentially offensive to a certain culture.

401
00:25:29,412 --> 00:25:32,494
Or maybe it just is not in the right place.

402
00:25:32,534 --> 00:25:33,454
Maybe it shouldn't be there.

403
00:25:33,794 --> 00:25:38,996
But this was a game in Tekken Fighter where they had the inscriptions,

404
00:25:39,096 --> 00:25:41,997
the Arabic script for Allah on the floor.

405
00:25:42,577 --> 00:25:45,599
And so, you know, now how discoverable is it though?

406
00:25:45,899 --> 00:25:46,819
That's the issue here.

407
00:25:46,839 --> 00:25:49,740
Because if you look at these tiles, when you're up here,

408
00:25:49,760 --> 00:25:52,861
your eyes are up here fighting, are you going to notice it in the tiles?

409
00:25:53,562 --> 00:25:57,085
And that is open to interpretation.

410
00:25:57,206 --> 00:26:00,629
Some people might notice, as some people did, and some people may not.

411
00:26:01,109 --> 00:26:08,077
And so, sometimes you'll put content elements into your environment that might be controversial,

412
00:26:08,097 --> 00:26:12,181
or they might be edgy or something, but sometimes you're not going to see them.

413
00:26:12,641 --> 00:26:16,025
And this is actually one of the things I do a lot when I do my consulting work in this area,

414
00:26:16,345 --> 00:26:18,807
is I look for things that most people are never going to see.

415
00:26:18,828 --> 00:26:22,992
And the only way I can do that is because I've got like God mode tools when I'm actually in the

416
00:26:23,032 --> 00:26:27,236
environment during one of the game builds, so I can like turn around and look at places that

417
00:26:27,296 --> 00:26:30,479
no one's ever going to see, or probably will never going to see.

418
00:26:31,910 --> 00:26:36,412
So let's talk a little more about real world context, because again, I want to make this distinction.

