00:27:44,864 --> 00:27:48,264
but maybe not because it's been enhanced in some way.

439
00:27:48,704 --> 00:27:54,025
And you know, this can be dangerous because if you take the wrong object and enhance it

440
00:27:54,065 --> 00:27:56,866
or augment it in a certain way, that might not work.

441
00:27:57,266 --> 00:28:02,046
Especially if it's a sacred site, if it's a church or a mosque or a synagogue or someplace

442
00:28:02,066 --> 00:28:06,007
like that, or if it's a burial site or something like that, you have to be really careful

443
00:28:06,027 --> 00:28:09,648
about what you do to actual locations because it can be very sensitive.

444
00:28:10,668 --> 00:28:14,251
Accuracy too. Does anyone know who this is or who it looks like?

445
00:28:17,233 --> 00:28:19,255
So basically they were modeling it after

446
00:28:20,136 --> 00:28:27,441
So now the funny thing is though is that when the developers made this model, I said that's Bill Clinton and they said who?

447
00:28:28,354 --> 00:28:32,837
They said, what? Because the team, there was a Japanese team who made this character,

448
00:28:32,877 --> 00:28:36,100
and so they weren't as familiar with the US president.

449
00:28:36,180 --> 00:28:40,503
So, but I'm like, I'm like, I was like, I know he's not exactly the same,

450
00:28:40,543 --> 00:28:44,205
but it's just like, but he also had a southern drawl when the character talks.

451
00:28:44,285 --> 00:28:44,826
I'm just like.

452
00:28:45,346 --> 00:28:49,987
This is like really similar, so you could, and so part of the problem too though,

453
00:28:50,327 --> 00:28:53,088
now if someone was to perceive that this is Bill Clinton,

454
00:28:53,468 --> 00:28:57,108
one of the things that we had to take out of the game is that this president in the game

455
00:28:57,248 --> 00:28:58,889
used the term the final solution.

456
00:28:59,309 --> 00:29:01,429
We all know the historical problem with that term.

457
00:29:01,869 --> 00:29:03,350
And so that was a huge issue.

458
00:29:03,410 --> 00:29:08,131
So you could be saying that well actually President Bill Clinton is in favor of this term,

459
00:29:08,191 --> 00:29:09,771
which of course is not true.

460
00:29:10,551 --> 00:29:13,192
So it's that kind of thing that people might perceive.

461
00:29:14,139 --> 00:29:17,461
Interpretation. So here's a really interesting example of history.

462
00:29:17,921 --> 00:29:22,423
So in Age of Empires, this is what history really showed what happened,

463
00:29:22,483 --> 00:29:27,165
is that the Yamatos in blue in Japan, they invaded the Korean Peninsula over there

464
00:29:27,545 --> 00:29:31,406
and they took over the Choson Empire in red. That's what really happened.

465
00:29:31,847 --> 00:29:34,168
So when Age of Empires was released in Korea,

466
00:29:34,208 --> 00:29:37,309
the Korean Ministry of Information said that never happened.

467
00:29:38,261 --> 00:29:39,382
So then what are you supposed to do?

468
00:29:40,042 --> 00:29:45,405
So basically what we ended up doing eventually was creating a patch only for Korea that showed

469
00:29:45,465 --> 00:29:46,185
the opposite.

470
00:29:46,225 --> 00:29:49,046
So the Choson are actually invading Japan instead.

471
00:29:49,527 --> 00:29:52,208
And so that's a matter of interpretation.

472
00:29:52,228 --> 00:29:54,509
A lot of people would say, well that's completely erroneous.

473
00:29:54,669 --> 00:29:57,091
It's like they should not do that in a historical game.

474
00:29:57,711 --> 00:29:58,751
Yeah, but guess what?

475
00:29:59,072 --> 00:30:02,874
Asian empires also had tanks in the Aztec empire.

476
00:30:03,474 --> 00:30:04,514
Aztecs never had tanks.

477
00:30:05,475 --> 00:30:10,096
The Aztec tanks were cool, but that doesn't mean, you know, there are inaccuracies in Age of Empires.

478
00:30:10,176 --> 00:30:12,696
It was not meant to be exactly precise history.

479
00:30:13,156 --> 00:30:17,798
But this is obviously a huge issue when we basically have to turn around and say,

480
00:30:17,818 --> 00:30:20,678
okay, well, they have a completely different interpretation of history.

481
00:30:21,979 --> 00:30:24,059
Or appropriateness. This is pretty straightforward.

482
00:30:24,679 --> 00:30:30,941
Killing Sikhs inside the Golden Temple in Amritsar, which is the most sacred site to the Sikh faith.

483
00:30:31,401 --> 00:30:32,481
That's pretty controversial.

484
00:30:33,219 --> 00:30:37,563
So that's like, you know, gunning down Catholics in St. Peter's in Rome, or

485
00:30:37,583 --> 00:30:41,888
you know, gunning down Muslims in Mecca. It's like, you just don't do it. That's a

486
00:30:42,068 --> 00:30:45,872
that's a sacred site. And so that's probably not going to be appropriate.

487
00:30:47,386 --> 00:30:53,409
The other thing that's interesting is that these are not just single variable things.

488
00:30:53,449 --> 00:30:57,291
A lot of these examples can be both inaccurate or inappropriate.

489
00:30:57,931 --> 00:31:02,393
This one was interesting where they were striving for accuracy in this simulator

490
00:31:02,433 --> 00:31:05,355
where you try and kill John F. Kennedy in Dallas.

491
00:31:05,855 --> 00:31:09,976
So you try and assassinate him from the book depository.

492
00:31:10,396 --> 00:31:12,636
And so the guys who made this game said,

493
00:31:12,656 --> 00:31:14,437
well, it's just a historical simulation.

494
00:31:14,457 --> 00:31:16,697
It's like, but it also kept score.

495
00:31:16,717 --> 00:31:19,758
And it wanted you to try and do a better job.

496
00:31:19,818 --> 00:31:21,098
And it's like, well, that's a game.

497
00:31:22,418 --> 00:31:25,279
So a lot of people felt this is highly inappropriate,

498
00:31:25,759 --> 00:31:27,619
but it's also highly accurate.

499
00:31:27,679 --> 00:31:31,020
They did an incredible job of recreating D. Lee Plaza in Dallas

500
00:31:31,380 --> 00:31:32,901
and recreating the whole scenario.

501
00:31:34,481 --> 00:31:37,307
Well, if you watch the Oliver Stone movie, though, then it's all baloney, right?

502
00:31:37,768 --> 00:31:41,074
So, let's talk about fictional world context now.

503
00:31:42,397 --> 00:31:46,978
So the primary issues that happen in the fictional world is sometimes we have generalization

504
00:31:46,998 --> 00:31:52,559
that happens where the developers kind of lump everything together, where it's like

505
00:31:52,579 --> 00:31:56,660
well all these cultures are the same, which kind of started happening in Jade Empire when

506
00:31:56,680 --> 00:32:00,761
we were creating that game, is that the idea that it was going to be a pan-Asian culture

507
00:32:00,801 --> 00:32:03,142
and yet in the initial form it was like 80% Chinese about...

508
00:32:06,043 --> 00:32:12,205
5% Japanese, 5% Korean, and the rest was Indian, excuse me, Hindu.

509
00:32:12,705 --> 00:32:16,447
And so it was kind of a weird mishmash of stuff, but it was heavily dominant in Chinese.

510
00:32:16,867 --> 00:32:20,048
And so, but the way that they had originally created it was sort of generalizing all those

511
00:32:20,108 --> 00:32:25,490
cultures as if to say they're all equivalent and they're all the same, which would be incredibly

512
00:32:25,530 --> 00:32:25,950
offensive.

513
00:32:27,831 --> 00:32:34,374
Emulation is, so this is probably the biggest issue in fictional worlds, and I'll give an example in a minute.

514
00:32:34,634 --> 00:32:41,036
But emulation is basically where you create something in your fictional universe that feels very much like something that exists here.

515
00:32:41,636 --> 00:32:49,920
Probably the number one thing I've seen in all my years is when they have a desert culture in a fantasy game that, my goodness, they look awfully Arab to me.

516
00:32:51,080 --> 00:32:53,782
Every single one of these cultures, every single one of these games

517
00:32:54,143 --> 00:32:57,305
have the same Arabic, Bedouin-looking feeling to them

518
00:32:57,325 --> 00:33:00,228
and it's like they just can't seem to depart that.

519
00:33:01,649 --> 00:33:05,392
Allegory is another big one as well, where basically you're suggesting something

520
00:33:05,452 --> 00:33:06,753
through the fictional universe

521
00:33:07,193 --> 00:33:08,334
and I'll explain that in a minute.

522
00:33:09,151 --> 00:33:12,494
And then the use of artifacts, too. This is a huge problem.

523
00:33:12,534 --> 00:33:15,597
This kind of relates to the backfilling and cultural evidence I mentioned before,

524
00:33:15,617 --> 00:33:20,081
where basically you're just throwing stuff in the environment to kind of flesh out the environment,

525
00:33:20,121 --> 00:33:24,945
but you're putting things in there that may or may not actually be useful in the fictional world,

526
00:33:25,025 --> 00:33:27,567
or might not fit with the logical consistency.

527
00:33:28,268 --> 00:33:33,209
So, a generalization, so this game got a lot of bad press because basically what they did

528
00:33:33,249 --> 00:33:37,851
is they took these different sets of deities, like the Norse gods and the Egyptian gods,

529
00:33:37,871 --> 00:33:39,931
but they also put in the Hindu gods.

530
00:33:40,371 --> 00:33:44,693
Now, yes, the Norse gods and the Egyptian gods are, they are still worshipped by a very,

531
00:33:44,753 --> 00:33:50,514
very small minority of human beings, whereas the Hindu faith is, you know, like about a

532
00:33:50,554 --> 00:33:51,175
billion people.

533
00:33:51,755 --> 00:33:56,099
So, you know, basically doing this equivalence and saying that, well, the Hindu gods are

534
00:33:56,139 --> 00:33:59,862
just the same as these other antiquated gods, we're just going to throw them in a mix and

535
00:33:59,902 --> 00:34:04,146
have them fight each other, that's a level of generalization that's not very acceptable.

536
00:34:05,768 --> 00:34:09,291
And so that can be potentially problematic, making that assumption.

537
00:34:10,481 --> 00:34:14,964
or emulation again, not picking on the Hindu faith, but this is a good example

538
00:34:15,424 --> 00:34:20,547
where this creature, this elephant demon, originally looked a lot like the god Ganesha

539
00:34:21,107 --> 00:34:26,030
and of course in this game, the elephant demon was an evil character that tried to kill you

540
00:34:26,070 --> 00:34:28,471
whereas Ganesha in the Hindu faith is a very benevolent

541
00:34:29,428 --> 00:34:32,089
very much a loved figure in their pantheon.

542
00:34:32,129 --> 00:34:34,530
And so, to create a character that emulates this...

543
00:34:34,590 --> 00:34:37,791
Now, the one you're seeing here is near the final form,

544
00:34:37,831 --> 00:34:40,532
whereas in its original form it looked a lot more like this,

545
00:34:40,612 --> 00:34:41,972
including another set of arms,

546
00:34:42,413 --> 00:34:44,914
which was, I think, kind of an obvious thing that had to be lost.

547
00:34:45,794 --> 00:34:49,195
But emulation happens a great deal when creating fantasy games.

548
00:34:50,376 --> 00:34:51,576
And allegory as well.

549
00:34:51,676 --> 00:34:55,837
So, if you don't know the story about the dervish and the arbiter character,

550
00:34:55,877 --> 00:34:56,118
if you've...

551
00:34:57,717 --> 00:35:01,438
have not played Halo, just to set this up really quick,

552
00:35:01,818 --> 00:35:04,759
this character, he serves a group called the Covenant,

553
00:35:05,079 --> 00:35:08,100
which is a kind of quasi-religious alien group.

554
00:35:08,440 --> 00:35:11,181
They worship the Halo rings that can destroy the galaxy.

555
00:35:11,521 --> 00:35:14,442
The Master Chief, main character of the game, is trying to stop them.

556
00:35:14,962 --> 00:35:18,303
And so, you know, that's basically the really, really short story.

557
00:35:18,804 --> 00:35:21,505
So this character that was originally called the Dervish,

558
00:35:21,925 --> 00:35:24,166
Dervish is a title from Sufi Islam,

559
00:35:24,186 --> 00:35:30,088
a specific title, very much the same way that Pope is a very specific title from Roman Catholicism.

560
00:35:30,528 --> 00:35:33,230
And so the original name of this character was Dervish.

561
00:35:33,670 --> 00:35:35,691
He serves one of three leaders of the covenant,

562
00:35:35,811 --> 00:35:37,451
one of whom is called the Prophet of Truth,

563
00:35:37,471 --> 00:35:39,612
which is an often used synonym for Muhammad.

564
00:35:41,974 --> 00:35:48,122
The Dervish serving the Prophet of Truth, and you've got the Master Chief, who is basically this quasi-American figure.

565
00:35:48,142 --> 00:35:53,128
I know it says UN Space Command on his shoulder, but come on, he's got an American accent and all that.

566
00:35:53,709 --> 00:35:57,994
So, he's trying to destroy the Covenant and stop them.

567
00:35:58,795 --> 00:36:05,543
And where the allegory starts getting built up here is that this was the first major game being released by Microsoft after 9-11.

568
00:36:05,583 --> 00:36:13,632
It was going to be one of the biggest games of the year, so it was very easy, at least for me, to see how people could perceive this as being an answer to 9-11.

569
00:36:14,634 --> 00:36:17,496
Where it's like, oh, so the Master Chief is going to destroy Islam

570
00:36:17,556 --> 00:36:20,838
because you've got the Prophet of Truth and the Dervish helping the Prophet of Truth

571
00:36:21,218 --> 00:36:22,179
and all this kind of stuff.

572
00:36:22,519 --> 00:36:24,681
And so that builds up a sense of allegory,

573
00:36:24,721 --> 00:36:27,583
that you're basically passing a message through the story.

574
00:36:28,003 --> 00:36:30,525
Now, there's a lot of great ways to do allegory in fiction.

575
00:36:30,565 --> 00:36:31,566
We see it all the time.

576
00:36:31,626 --> 00:36:35,568
Like, the original Star Trek series was masterful at doing allegory,

577
00:36:35,589 --> 00:36:38,370
where they were dealing with racial issues and gender issues,

578
00:36:38,731 --> 00:36:41,973
but they did it in such a way in the science fiction realm that made it okay,

579
00:36:42,333 --> 00:36:43,714
made it more palatable for the late 60s.

580
00:36:45,015 --> 00:36:48,177
So we have to be really careful about the messages that we're sending.

581
00:36:48,217 --> 00:36:51,739
I'm not saying you can't put a message into your game, into your fictional universe.

582
00:36:52,119 --> 00:36:53,020
We see it all the time.

583
00:36:53,120 --> 00:36:54,360
You look at stuff like Dragon Age.

584
00:36:54,380 --> 00:36:58,523
There's all kinds of stuff in Dragon Age about racial relations between the elves and humans

585
00:36:58,563 --> 00:36:58,983
and all that.

586
00:36:59,403 --> 00:37:00,724
And I think it's great that they do it.

587
00:37:00,764 --> 00:37:04,987
We just have to be really careful about what that allegory is saying and how it might relate

588
00:37:05,407 --> 00:37:06,468
to something in the real world.

589
00:37:07,662 --> 00:37:09,123
And then of course, artifacts too.

590
00:37:09,163 --> 00:37:11,585
So here's a great example in this game, Pocket God,

591
00:37:11,645 --> 00:37:14,526
where this artifact here, now the developer,

592
00:37:14,566 --> 00:37:16,828
they got pushback from the Polynesian community

593
00:37:16,848 --> 00:37:18,709
because a lot of Polynesian people were upset

594
00:37:19,109 --> 00:37:20,890
because of the way these little natives look,

595
00:37:20,910 --> 00:37:22,431
because it's a very antiquated version

596
00:37:22,451 --> 00:37:24,573
of an indigenous person with a bone in their hair.

597
00:37:25,033 --> 00:37:26,813
and a grass skirt and all that stuff.

598
00:37:27,094 --> 00:37:29,414
But the real issue here is that the developer said,

599
00:37:29,434 --> 00:37:31,175
well, this is no specific culture at all.

600
00:37:31,495 --> 00:37:32,235
It's like, really?

601
00:37:32,255 --> 00:37:34,636
Well, you know, that thing right there is a Moai

602
00:37:34,676 --> 00:37:36,257
that only exists on Easter Island.

603
00:37:36,297 --> 00:37:37,777
So by putting a Moai on the island,

604
00:37:37,797 --> 00:37:40,818
you've instantly made this the Easter Island culture.

605
00:37:41,419 --> 00:37:44,440
So that artifact pegged this particular game

606
00:37:44,480 --> 00:37:45,500
to a specific culture.

607
00:37:45,900 --> 00:37:47,121
Now, in later versions of the game,

608
00:37:47,161 --> 00:37:49,781
they actually changed it so that it's a different statue.

609
00:37:49,821 --> 00:37:51,062
It's not the actual Moai.

610
00:37:51,182 --> 00:37:53,463
So just simple things like that.

611
00:37:55,633 --> 00:37:59,194
Now, there are a lot of shared issues between the real world and fictional world, so logical

612
00:37:59,234 --> 00:38:03,455
consistency again, I'm going to keep mentioning that because it's such an important issue

613
00:38:03,675 --> 00:38:04,676
in world creation.

614
00:38:05,356 --> 00:38:08,117
It's always an issue whether you're dealing with real world or fictional world.

615
00:38:08,517 --> 00:38:12,458
Fictional world, it tends to be a bigger problem because you're creating things from scratch,

616
00:38:12,538 --> 00:38:16,840
and so you have more effort to actually make that world feel real as opposed to actually

617
00:38:16,920 --> 00:38:18,460
starting with a real world environment.

618
00:38:18,480 --> 00:38:21,521
Changing the creation of cultural evidence, which I've mentioned.

619
00:38:22,445 --> 00:38:26,606
Now, product versioning by language and locale is also very important.

620
00:38:26,967 --> 00:38:31,308
So the Age of Empires example I gave you about Korea, by having to make that fix, you now

621
00:38:31,348 --> 00:38:32,489
have two versions of the game.

622
00:38:32,529 --> 00:38:34,890
You've got the world version and you've got the Korean version.

623
00:38:35,290 --> 00:38:39,492
And so now you have to manage all of these versions, like these different perceptions

624
00:38:39,712 --> 00:38:44,494
of your content, you know, so that's something that gets really complicated very quickly.

625
00:38:45,374 --> 00:38:48,635
And then of course the discoverability of issues, which I already mentioned.

626
00:38:49,907 --> 00:38:55,448
So, talking about degree of complexity, so, what level of detail is required to realize

627
00:38:55,488 --> 00:38:57,428
the game's world for the intended experience?

628
00:38:57,448 --> 00:38:59,229
That's really the question you have to ask yourself.

629
00:38:59,569 --> 00:39:03,310
And again, I'm going to keep harping on the notion it's not about realism, it's about

630
00:39:03,350 --> 00:39:04,090
realization.

631
00:39:04,490 --> 00:39:10,071
You may not have to do much of anything to make that world work for what you intend for

632
00:39:10,091 --> 00:39:10,551
your game.

633
00:39:10,931 --> 00:39:14,812
And so you really have to step back and think about it, what's the most minimal amount I

634
00:39:14,892 --> 00:39:16,733
need to do to make the game work?

635
00:39:16,773 --> 00:39:19,673
And then you can think about maybe embellishing a little bit, if necessary.

636
00:39:19,814 --> 00:39:27,257
So one of the things geographers are really good at is we are very good at the realization of worlds because we spend all this time

637
00:39:27,317 --> 00:39:31,859
Deconstructing this one and we deconstruct like no other that's what we do

638
00:39:32,199 --> 00:39:37,902
And so we tear this world apart at least in our heads and we try and figure out what's where why are things there?

639
00:39:38,002 --> 00:39:42,564
And all that kind of stuff now cartography has always done this cartography is about

640
00:39:44,385 --> 00:39:46,145
It's about rebuilding the world.

641
00:39:46,465 --> 00:39:48,906
Because all cartography is subjective.

642
00:39:48,946 --> 00:39:52,668
If you look at a map and you think it's an accurate document, you're fooling yourself.

643
00:39:52,728 --> 00:39:58,190
Because every single map is gone, it goes through a subjective process through cartographers

644
00:39:58,830 --> 00:40:01,351
who make decisions about what's going to show up on the map.

645
00:40:01,611 --> 00:40:06,332
Now, yes, cartographers are committed to showing ground truth to make sure that what you see

646
00:40:06,392 --> 00:40:10,454
on the map is actually there, but you're not going to see everything that's there because

647
00:40:10,594 --> 00:40:12,395
you can't put everything on the map that's there.

648
00:40:12,935 --> 00:40:17,577
And so what we do is we conveniently divide the world up into layers.

649
00:40:18,418 --> 00:40:21,760
We've done this in our heads for centuries as cartographers,

650
00:40:21,820 --> 00:40:25,402
but now with geographic information systems, it's made it very explicit.

651
00:40:25,422 --> 00:40:27,443
Because this is how geographic information systems work.

652
00:40:28,264 --> 00:40:32,807
The world is divided up into layers, they have a base layer that is quote real world,

653
00:40:33,168 --> 00:40:37,711
it has the geoid and all the other stuff that it's built on, and they just have every kind

654
00:40:37,751 --> 00:40:39,032
of layer you can imagine on there.

655
00:40:39,333 --> 00:40:42,075
And in the same way when we build worlds, we kind of do the same thing.

656
00:40:42,135 --> 00:40:47,159
Now maybe we don't think about it this way, but that's one of the things I would hope

657
00:40:47,339 --> 00:40:51,282
people do think about it this way, because they really should start thinking about the

658
00:40:51,622 --> 00:40:55,366
kind of the layers of the world that they're creating, and you may or may not need some

659
00:40:55,386 --> 00:40:57,267
of the world, excuse me, some of the layers.

660
00:40:58,377 --> 00:41:02,219
So I'm just going to talk about a few of these potential layers, well I'm not going to really

661
00:41:02,259 --> 00:41:04,120
